aa(lp23
VLet's build a better map of the world.
p24
aVAnd we can start by overcoming some ancient mythology.
p25
aVThere's a saying with which all students of history are familiar:
p26
aV"Geography is destiny."
p27
aVSounds so grave, doesn't it?
p28
aVIt's such a fatalistic adage.
p29
aVIt tells us that landlocked countries are condemned to be poor,
p30
aVthat small countries cannot escape their larger neighbors,
p31
aVthat vast distances are insurmountable.
p32
aVBut every journey I take around the world,
p33
aVI see an even greater force sweeping the planet:
p34
aVconnectivity.
p35
aa(lp36
VThe global connectivity revolution, in all of its forms \u2014
p37
aVtransportation, energy and communications \u2014
p38
aVhas enabled such a quantum leap in the mobility of people,
p39
aVof goods, of resources, of knowledge,
p40
aVsuch that we can no longer even think of geography as distinct from it.
p41
aVIn fact, I view the two forces as fusing together
p42
aVinto what I call "connectography."
p43
aa(lp44
VConnectography represents a quantum leap
p45
aVin the mobility of people, resources and ideas,
p46
aVbut it is an evolution,
p47
aVan evolution of the world from political geography,
p48
aVwhich is how we legally divide the world,
p49
aVto functional geography,
p50
aVwhich is how we actually use the world,
p51
aVfrom nations and borders, to infrastructure and supply chains.
p52
aa(lp53
VOur global system is evolving
p54
aVfrom the vertically integrated empires of the 19th century,
p55
aVthrough the horizontally interdependent nations of the 20th century,
p56
aVinto a global network civilization in the 21st century.
p57
aVConnectivity, not sovereignty,
p58
aVhas become the organizing principle of the human species.
p59
aa(lp60
V(Applause)
